<paragraph blockId="23.[812,1457,1587,2028]" box="[813,913,1587,1613]" pageId="23" pageNumber="28">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[812,1457,1587,2028]" pageId="23" pageNumber="28">
Of the three species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yabe &amp; Hatai" authorityYear="1934" box="[1074,1219,1618,1644]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Dallinidae" genus="Nipponithyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebratulida" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1074,1219,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="28">Nipponithyris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
so far recorded from modern seas (
<bibRefCitation author="LOGAN A." box="[963,1099,1650,1676]" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" pagination="3082 - 3115" refId="ref21036" refString="LOGAN A. 2007. - Geographic distribution of extant articulated brachiopods, in SELDEN P. A. (ed.), Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology. Part H. Brachiopoda Revised. Geological Society of America and University of Kansas. Boulder, Colorado and Lawrence, Kansas, vol. 6: 3082 - 3115." type="journal article" year="2007">Logan 2007</bibRefCitation>
; Bitner 2008) 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cooper" authorityYear="1973" box="[1259,1336,1650,1676]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Dallinidae" genus="Nipponithyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebratulida" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="afra">
<emphasis box="[1259,1336,1650,1676]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="28">N. afra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only one from the Indian 
<taxonomicName authority="Bitner &amp; Logan, 2016" authorityName="Bitner &amp; Logan" authorityYear="2016" box="[1058,1134,1682,1708]" genus="Ocean" pageId="23" pageNumber="5" rank="genus" status="new species, new genus">Ocean</taxonomicName>
, occurring off 
<collectingCountry box="[1307,1456,1682,1708]" name="Mozambique" pageId="23" pageNumber="28">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
at depths of 
<quantity box="[961,1089,1714,1741]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="9.6" metricValueMin="7.4" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" unit="m" value="850.0" valueMax="960.0" valueMin="740.0">740-960 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="COOPER G. A." box="[1106,1277,1714,1740]" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 45" refId="ref19340" refString="COOPER G. A. 1973 a. - New Brachiopoda from the Indian Ocean. Smithsonian Contributions to Paleobiology 16: 1 - 45." type="journal article" year="1973">Cooper 1973a</bibRefCitation>
). This species is characterized by a smooth, sulcate shell, strongly thickened posteriorly. The specimens identified here, which extend the species’ depth range, are generally larger in the mature stage than those described by 
<bibRefCitation author="COOPER G. A." box="[1081,1257,1842,1868]" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 45" refId="ref19340" refString="COOPER G. A. 1973 a. - New Brachiopoda from the Indian Ocean. Smithsonian Contributions to Paleobiology 16: 1 - 45." type="journal article" year="1973">Cooper (1973a)</bibRefCitation>
but are otherwise closely similar. 
<figureCitation box="[976,1070,1873,1899]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="25.[132,143,1541,1559]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1497]" captionTargetId="figure-135@25.[132,1455,214,1497]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIG. 16. — Nipponithyris afra Cooper, 1973: A-H, dorsal, lateral and anterior views of complete specimens (MNHN IB-2013-89-91), North-West Madagascar, off Majumga, MIRIKY, stn CP 3252, 850-900 m; I, J, inner views of ventral valve (MNHN IB-2013-92), and tilted (J) to show swollen bases and grooves to accommodate inner socket ridges, SEM, North-West Madagascar, between Majumga and Cap Saint-André, MIRIKY, stn CP 3278, 750-780 m; K, L, inner and oblique views of dorsal valve (MNHN IB-2013-93) to show brachial loop, SEM, Mozambique Channel, Inhambane transect, MAINBAZA, stn CP 3139, 1092-1195 m. Scale bars: A-H, 5 mm; I-L, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4578198" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4578198/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="28">Fig. 16K</figureCitation>
shows the complete loop in an early terebratelliform stage from MAINBAZA station 3139 and may be compared with one of Cooper’s 
<typeStatus box="[1249,1350,1938,1964]" pageId="23" pageNumber="28">paratypes</typeStatus>
shown in his plate 7, fig. 19. In the studied material 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cooper" authorityYear="1973" box="[1266,1455,1969,1995]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Dallinidae" genus="Nipponithyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebratulida" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="afra">
<emphasis box="[1266,1455,1969,1995]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="28">Nipponithyris afra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the commonest species (more than 
<specimenCount box="[1282,1444,2001,2028]" pageId="23" pageNumber="28" type="generic">120 specimens</specimenCount>
).
</paragraph>
